1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 {This move gives up the centre every quickly,
which isn't a very good idea. It also goes against the French Defence idea. So
that's why I don't think this move is the best for Black.} 4. Nxe4 Bd7 {This
bishop is going to find an excellent place on c6. The alternative is...} (4...
Nd7) 5. Nf3 {White is simply going to follow the openings tasks until move
number 8.} Bc6 6. Bd3 Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 8. Ng3 $1 {This move has a very simple
idea. In general, in this variation it is not favourable for White to exchange
pieces because of his space advantage.} Be7 9. c4 {Winning more space.} O-O 10.
b3 {Preparing the development of the bishop. b2 is an excellent square,
because from here the bishop has hidden potential.} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 c6 {This is
what Black is looking for in this system: exchange the bad bishop and obtain a
solid position. Of course, this is very good for White, with a bishop pair and
space advantage.} 12. Bb2 Qa5 13. a3 $1 {Preventing the exchange of the
bishops with Ba3. This move is very important to maintain the advantage. Now
Black has two main alternatives.} b5 {It's the second main alternative.} (13...
Rfe8 {Is the main alternative of the position.} 14. Rfe1 Rad8 15. Re2 Nf8 16.
h4 {And White has good possibilities.}) 14. cxb5 cxb5 15. Rfe1 {Activating the
rook and, at the same time, threatening moves like Nf5.} Nd5 16. Nf5 N7f6 17.
Nxe7+ Nxe7 {White has two bishops against two knights.} 18. Bc3 Qd8 (18... Qb6
{Probably a better move.} 19. Bb4 $1 Nc6 $1 20. Bxf8 Rxf8 $16) 19. Bxb5 {White
is a pawn up - the rest is easy.} Nfd5 20. Bb2 Qb6 21. Bc4 Rfd8 22. Rad1 Nc6
23. b4 Rac8 24. Bd3 Nf6 25. d5 Nxd5 26. Qe4 g6 27. h4 Nde7 28. Bc4 Nf5 29. Bxe6
fxe6 30. Qxe6+ 1-0

