1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bd3 {
This move has the advantage, in relation to Bc4, of making a kingside attack
possible. The bishop is better placed on d3 than on c4. The problem is that
White can't use the "d" file.} c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O {This is one of the most
typical pawn structures in this variation. It has the following points: 1. a
queen side majority for White. 2. There is no clear weaknesses on this
position. 3. White's pieces are pointing to the king side.} O-O 10. Qe2 b6 11.
Bg5 Bb7 12. Rad1 Qc7 {For Black, it's better to allow the doubled pawns than
keep the knight pinned.} (12... Qe7 13. Ne5 h6 14. Bh4 $14 g5 {Doesn't look
very good for Black.} 15. Bg3 {And, at some point, h4 - attacking Black's weak
position.}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 {Let's evaluate this position. White has a better
pawn structure and a safer king; Black has the bishop pair; so after White's
next move, the position is a slight advantage for White.} 14. Be4 $1 Rfd8 15.
c3 Kh8 16. g3 {White is consolidating his position.} Bf8 17. a3 Bg7 18. Bxb7
Qxb7 19. Rd3 {The "d" file has a special importance in this variation.
Dominating it can give you great chances.} f5 20. Rfd1 Rxd3 21. Rxd3 Bf6 22.
Qd1 Rc8 $2 23. Ne1 $2 (23. Rd7 Rc7 24. Qd6 $1 {This is probably the move Emms
didn't see.}) 23... b5 24. Ng2 Qb6 25. Nf4 Rd8 26. Nh5 Be7 27. Qd2 $1 Rxd3 28.
Qh6 $1 1-0

